            <h3>Background</h3>

            <p>Dr. Lavian holds a Ph.D. in Computer Science from UC Berkeley, specializing in network communications, and spent nearly 20 years researching, studying, and lecturing at UC Berkeley&rsquo;s College of Engineering. He served as Principal Scientist and Principal Architect at Nortel Networks (1996&ndash;2007) and as a DARPA Principal Investigator on multimedia network research projects. Dr. Lavian has over 120 <a href="/patents/">patents</a> including innovations in real-time media delivery and network streaming, over 25 <a href="/scientific-publications/">scientific publications</a>, and has been retained in over 70 <a href="/cases-expert-witness-testimony/">cases</a>, including 80+ depositions, before U.S. federal courts, PTAB, ITC, and international tribunals.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="two-col">
          <div>
            <h3>Streaming Protocols: H.323, SIP &amp; RTP</h3>

            <p>Dr. Lavian&rsquo;s expertise covers the principal streaming and conferencing protocols. H.323 is an ITU standard for audio/video conferencing whose architecture includes gatekeepers, media gateways, and endpoints. SIP (Session Initiation Protocol), developed by the <a href="https://www.ietf.org/" target="_blank">IETF</a>, is an HTTP-based signaling protocol that manages interactive sessions for voice, video, chat, and instant messaging. SIP supports challenge-based authentication, end-to-end encryption via S/MIME, and is transport-independent.</p>

            <p>RTP (Real-Time Transport Protocol) and RTCP (RTP Control Protocol) handle the media layer. RTP provides end-to-end transport for real-time audio and video over UDP, while RTCP provides feedback on transmission quality. Dr. Lavian analyzes these protocols at the specification level for patent claim construction, infringement, and validity assessments.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3>Protocol Expertise in <a href="/communications-expert-witness/network-security-expert/">Security</a> &amp; Transport</h3>

            <p>Dr. Lavian&rsquo;s streaming media expertise extends to SIP authentication mechanisms, SIP proxy server architectures, codec negotiation (H.264, H.265, VP9, AV1), adaptive bitrate streaming (HLS, DASH), content delivery network (CDN) architectures, and WebRTC browser-based communications. This protocol-level knowledge is applied in patent disputes involving real-time media delivery, conferencing systems, and unified communications platforms.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

